pullRequest.body:
These are (in my opinion) improperly named things that I encountered over time. Happy to remove any of them if there are disagreements.
* Remove manual instance names `IccManifold` and `Icc_smooth_manifold`. They're improper because the former is a `ChartedSpace` instance, while the latter is a `SmoothManifoldWithCorners` instance. As instances, they also probably shouldn't come up so high when searching for "Manifold" in the docs. Their names are now automatically generated, just like the two instances below them.
* Rename `ManifoldWithCorners.metrizableSpace` to `Manifold.metrizableSpace`.
* Rename `apply_(h)fdifferential` to `(h)fdifferential_apply`. This is to match the semantics of e.g. `ite_apply` and `apply_ite`.

---

Thanks for starting the conversation! Here are my thoughts in the renames. Some of them are definitely good; it could be good to split this PR.

If we rename `halfspace` to `halfSpace`, we should be consistent about it. Can you fix all other mentions of "halfspace" in mathlib as well, please? (At this point, this would make a good separate PR.)
Yes, I'll start a new PR just for `halfspace` -> `halfSpace`.

I agree that renaming this to `IccChartedSpace` makes sense. I have used this instance name, though --- so I'm not sure if removing it actually improves anything. (What does the autogenerated name look like?)

`IccChartedSpace` sounds good. The auto generated names are ugly. See the [two instances that follow](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Geometry/Manifold/Instances/Real.html#instChartedSpaceEuclideanHalfSpaceOfNatNatElemRealIcc). Should we rename those two as well? Perhaps `IccZeroOneChartedSpace`? I don't see these names used anywhere within mathlib, so I assume your usage is confined to a branch of yours.
Renaming those seems fine. I would leave out the 0 and 1 from the names, though --- mathematically, these are not important (to me). My usage is in a PR to mathlib, and indeed not merged yet.
On 0 and 1, see my comment below.
Similarly, I'd prefer to think again: what's the auto-generated name? (The current name is not good, renaming to IccSmoothManifoldWithCorners is fine with me.)
`Icc_smoothManifoldWithCorners` because `SmoothManifoldWithCorners` is a `Prop`. The instance below that could be renamed `Icc_zero_one_smoothManifoldWithCorners`?
Agreed on the Prop. I think omitting `zero_one` is clearer.

Just to be sure, `Icc_smooth_manifold` refers to `Icc x y`. There's another instance below it referring to `Icc 0 1`, which is currently unnamed (long autogenerated name). I'm suggesting renaming them `Icc_smoothManifoldWithCorners` and `Icc_zero_one_smoothManifoldWithCorners`, respectively.

I find the new name confusing: the *manifold* is metrizable, not the model. `SmoothManifoldWithCorners.metrizableSpace` would be acceptable with me --- but then, the point is that this lemma does not require smoothness (the doc-string even says "topological manifold"). Overall, I'm inclined to let this be. What do you think?

I see your point, but I'm not sure `ManifoldWithCorners` explains the theorem statement, either. It is also strange to have one and exactly one item under the namespace `ManifoldWithCorners`, when it isn't a thing on its own.

The way mathlib defines manifolds (with corners) is already not straightforward. I worry that it would be confusing for somebody looking for the manifold API to first stumble on `ManifoldWithCorners` thinking that it is a good starting point.

A descriptive name might be `TopologicalSpace.metrizableSpace_of_finiteDimensional_sigmaCompact_t2`, following [`TopologicalSpace.metrizableSpace_of_t3_second_countable`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/Metrizable/Urysohn.html#TopologicalSpace.metrizableSpace_of_t3_second_countable).
The instance you quoted is misnamed; filed #18911 for fixing it. Review welcome :-)
This instance is about manifolds, though (and the instance for charted spaces already exists --- this is merely a convenience shortcut/serves to point readers to this fact).

Ok, I think `Manifold.metrizableSpace` is also fine, following [`Manifold.locallyCompact_of_finiteDimensional`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Geometry/Manifold/SmoothManifoldWithCorners.html#Manifold.locallyCompact_of_finiteDimensional). I'm also fine with the latter being renamed `ManifoldWithCorners.locallyCompact_of_finiteDimensional` for consistency.
Okay then: both seem fine enough for me; can you make that rename? (Or, if you prefer another opinion: ask a maintainer for a preference between those two?)

I'll choose `Manifold.` for three reasons.
* `Manifold.locallyCompact_of_finiteDimensional` came first in 2019 (metrizable statement came in 2022).
* There is an existing meaningful namespace called `Manifold`, which contains notations for the API based on `ModelWithCorners`.
* It is much shorter.
This rename is fine with me. Feel free to file an `easy` PR with just it.
This also *seems* like a fine change to me.

I just realised: I think the point of these instances is not to be *used* --- but merely to show that they are present. (They are, in fact, subsumed by the instances above.) In other words: I'm not sure if naming these is actually useful. (Adding a comment about this is certainly welcome.)
